==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mulberry
<hw>Mul"ber*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Mulberries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>moolbery</ets>,
<ets>murberie</ets>, AS. <ets>murberie</ets>, where the first part is
fr. L. <ets>morum</ets> mulberry; cf. Gr. <?/, <?/. Cf. <er>Murrey</er>,
<er>Sycamore</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>The berry
or fruit of any tree of the genus <gen>Morus</gen>; also, the tree
itself. See <er>Morus</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A dark pure color, like the hue of a black
mulberry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mulberry mass</b></col>. <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <cd>See
<er>Morula</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Paper mulberry</b></col>, <cd>a tree
(<spn>Broussonetia papyrifera</spn>), related to the true mulberry, used
in Polynesia for making tapa cloth by macerating and pounding the inner
bark, and in China and Japan for the manufacture of paper. It is seen as
a shade tree in America.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mulberry-faced</ent>⟦br⟧
